{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"17ce9c7c-7b35-4e7f-a2e3-6784877d9f8e","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the container:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool binary in or use a sidecar/ephemeral container.\n- For lower overhead or longer captures, consider `dotnet-monitor` (runs as a sidecar) or Linux `perf` for OS-level profiling.\n- Use `kubectl cp` to pull the trace file out of the pod.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"46e530a2-24c0-4385-bf08-9005d4894c98","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":315,"requestId":"2C44:97105:12BAFD6:154D353:69F94719"},"id":"f5cc90ce-90fc-4f58-bd47-df39bad6785e","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:25:54.167Z","parentId":"0c23f729-bb10-4263-80bb-fce541d0e838"}
